# Agent Operating Contract

All AI agents operating in this project must follow these rules.
Copy this to your project root as `AGENTS.md` and customize for your setup.

This file ensures consistent behavior across Claude, Codex, Gemini, or any
other AI agent that works on your codebase.

---

## 1. Knowledge Base First — ALWAYS

Before starting ANY non-trivial task, search the knowledge base:

```bash
kb search "your topic"
```

Or use MCP tools: `kb_search`, `kb_context`, `kb_search_smart`

**Why:** The KB accumulates institutional memory. Searching first prevents
repeating solved problems, avoids known pitfalls, and saves tokens.

**Token-efficient retrieval order:**
1. `kb_context` — summaries only (~98% fewer tokens than full docs)
2. `kb_search` — full-text ranked results with snippets
3. `kb_read` — full document content (only when you need details)

---

## 2. NEVER Do Destructive Actions Without Backup

**Rules:**
- Before ANY destructive action (delete files, drop tables, destroy instances):
  ask "Is there data that hasn't been backed up?"
- BACKUP FIRST. Always. No exceptions.
- Never `rm -rf` on user data without explicit confirmation
- Never `git push --force` to main/master
- Never drop database tables without backup confirmation

---

## 3. Capture Session Findings — MANDATORY

At the END of every significant session, capture what happened.

Use the KB MCP tools:
- `kb_capture_session` — for debugging/implementation sessions
- `kb_capture_fix` — for bug fixes with symptom/cause/resolution

**What MUST be captured:**
- Any error that took more than 5 minutes to diagnose
- Any workaround or non-obvious fix
- Any architectural decision and WHY
- Any failed approach (so we don't try it again)

**Why:** Agents lose context every session. The KB is shared memory.
If you don't capture it, the next agent will waste time re-discovering it.

---

## 4. Multi-Agent Coordination

When multiple agents work on the same project:
- All agents read/write to the SAME knowledge base
- Search KB before starting — another agent may have already solved it
- Capture your work so other agents benefit
- Don't contradict decisions another agent made without flagging it

**Consensus model:** When agents disagree, go with what the majority agrees on
and incorporate unique points from each perspective.

---

## 5. Code Standards

- Simplicity over cleverness
- Fix root causes, not symptoms
- DRY, YAGNI — don't over-engineer
- Run tests before claiming work is done
- Prefer editing existing files over creating new ones
- Never commit .env files, credentials, or API keys

---

## 6. The Self-Learning Loop

This project uses a self-learning development workflow:

```
Agent works on task
  -> Captures session findings to KB
  -> KB synthesizes across sessions
  -> Insights get promoted to lessons/decisions
  -> Agent instructions auto-update
  -> Next session starts smarter
  -> Repeat
```

Every agent contributes to this loop. The system compounds intelligence over time.

---

## 7. When In Doubt

- Search the KB first
- Ask the user — don't guess on architectural decisions
- Don't silently make destructive changes
- Capture your findings before your session ends
